sentences: Gwendolen Avril Coleridge-Taylor (8 March 1903 – 21 December 1998) was an English pianist, conductor, and composer.
On 19 April 1924 Coleridge-Taylor married Harold Dashwood, in the Croydon parish church.
Coleridge-Taylor was invited on a tour of South Africa in 1952, during the period of apartheid,
In 1939, she moved to Buxted in East Sussex where she had views over the South Downs.
Coleridge-Taylor died in Seaford on the Sussex coast in late 1998.
In 1998 a blue plaque was placed at the nursing home where she spent her last days, Stone's House, Crouch Lane, Seaford.

Later, she won a scholarship for composition and piano at Trinity College of Music in 1915, where she was taught by Gordon Jacob and Alec Rowley.
In 1933 she made her formal debut as a conductor at the Royal Albert Hall.
She was the founder and conductor of both the Coleridge-Taylor Symphony Orchestra and its accompanying musical society in 1941, intended to give employment to musicians during the depression.
In 1956 Coleridge-Taylor arranged and conducted the spirituals performed in a BBC radio version of Marc Connelly's (nowadays controversial) play The Green Pastures.
